"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-paris-2024-olympics-when-will-akani-simbine-contest-the-100m-event\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbParis 2024 Olympics: When will Akani Simbine contest the 100m event?  Akani Simbine will be desperate to go one better in Paris.  Akani Simbine has progressed in the last two editions of the Summer Olympics. Can he claim a podium place at the 2024 Paris Olympics?  Akani Simbine ran a time of 9.93 seconds at Tokyo 2020 in the 100m final. That meant he missed a bronze medal by a heartbreaking four-hundredths of a second behind Canada's Andre De Grasse. Italy's Marcell Jacobs was the surprise gold medalist four years ago in a wide-open field that Simbine fancied his chances of winning. Four years before that, Simbine came fifth in the 100m final in Rio De Janeiro; the medalists that night were the legendary Jamaican Usain Bolt with gold, USA's Justin Gatlin claiming silver and De Grasse scooping the bronze. Rio 2016 and Tokyo 2020 contain painful 'what if' thoughts and memories for Simbine, but Paris 2024 can change all of that.  After battling depression and disenchantment with the sport, Simbine is now just a \\\"kid that is running for fun\\\" again.  \\\"I did everything I needed to do for track or the sport, I ate right, I sacrificed time with my family, I did all these things,\\\" Simbine said in an exclusiveinterview with Olympics.com.  \\\"I was just the athlete, I pushed everything away and still got disappointed. When I got disappointed, I had nothing to run back to. I had nothing that was my foundation or my security because now my whole identity does not know anything else than track. I was supposed to get a medal and now I did not get a medal. So now what must happen?\\\"  Thepreliminary roundof theMen's 100m event is on Saturday 03 August at 10:35 SA time. That's followed byRound 1at11:45.Sunday 04 August sees the semi-finals at 20:00and then thegrand final,where Simbine will hope to line up, at21:50.  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.com. You can also send a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1. Follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor your social fix. Check out our dedicatedParis 2024page for the latest from the French capital.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cap